"title": "7470: temple, significance of",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7470",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>The temple was both idealised and spiritualised by OT and NT writers.</p>\n<h2>The OT concept of an ideal temple in the future age of salvation</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa2:3\">ISA 2:3</a></strong> parallel <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mic4:2\">MIC 4:2</a> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa56:4-Isa56:7\">ISA 56:4–56:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa66:20\">ISA 66:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer33:11\">JER 33:11</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek37:28\">EZK 37:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:2-Ezek40:4\">EZK 40:2–40:4</a> <em>Ezekiel received a vision of a rebuilt temple to which the glory of the LORD had returned. Chapters 40–48 describe this temple and its worship in detail</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hag2:6-Hag2:8\">HAG 2:6–2:8</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech14:16\">ZEC 14:16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mal3:1-Mal3:3\">MAL 3:1–3:3</a></p>\n<h2>The superstitious belief that the presence of the temple in Jerusalem safeguarded the city</h2>\n<h3>The origin of such a belief</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs19:32-2Kgs19:36\">2KI 19:32–19:36</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps132:13-Ps132:18\">PSA 132:13–132:18</a></p>\n<h3>The prophets knew that disobedience to God would be judged in spite of the temple</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mic3:12\">MIC 3:12</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer7:4\">JER 7:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer7:12-Jer7:14\">JER 7:12–7:14</a></p>\n<h2>The link between the earthly temple and heaven</h2>\n<h3>Heaven is described as God's temple</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps11:4\">PSA 11:4</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hab2:20\">HAB 2:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb8:5\">HEB 8:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb9:24\">HEB 9:24</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev11:19\">REV 11:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev14:15-Rev14:17\">REV 14:15–14:17</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev15:5-Rev15:8\">REV 15:5–15:8</a></p>\n<h3>The ultimate ``city of God'' needs no temple, since it is permeated by God's presence</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev21:22\">REV 21:22</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rev21:3\">REV 21:3</a></p>\n<h2>The risen Christ as the temple where God's glory is revealed</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/John2:19-John2:21\">JHN 2:19–2:21</a></strong></p>\n<h2>The church as the temple where God's presence dwells</h2>\n<h3>The individual believer as the temple of the Holy Spirit</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor6:19\">1CO 6:19</a></strong></p>\n<h3>The local church as God's temple</h3>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Cor3:16-1Cor3:17\">1CO 3:16–3:17</a></p>\n<h3>The whole church as God's temple</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Eph2:21-Eph2:22\">EPH 2:21–2:22</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor6:16\">2CO 6:16</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Pet2:5\">1PE 2:5</a> <em>“house” here alludes to the temple. The church offers not animal sacrifices but “spiritual sacrifices” of praise and service.</em></p>",
